---
import PNotes from "../components/PNotes.astro";
import BrowserSupport from "../components/BrowserSupport.astro";
---

<p-slide class="cover-internal">
  <h1>Space &amp; fluidity</h1>

  <PNotes>
    <p>Shift from color to spacing — same principle, browser does the math.</p>
    <p>Not just colors: layout values can become dynamic too.</p>
    <p>The enemy here: hard-coded breakpoints and stepped scales.</p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h3 class="main-gradient">Death by breakpoints</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      📐 <span>Fixed steps = </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >awkward in-between sizes</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      🔁 <span>Every step needs </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >another media query</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      🌊 <span>What we want: </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >continuous scaling</span
      >
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>Everyone has a _typography.scss with five breakpoints. Get the nod.</p>
    <p>
      The problem is not media queries themselves — the problem is using them to
      fake continuous behavior with hard-coded jumps.
    </p>
    <p>Pitch clamp() as the cure on the next slide.</p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide b-a>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Type scale</span> — stepped by breakpoints 🌊
  </h5>
  <div class="cols">
    <div p-effect="from left">
      <p class="tag">
        Before — <span class="main-sub-gradient">media query steps</span>
      </p>
      <pre
        class="small-line"
        data-label-file="type.css">
        <code style="font-size: 0.55em" is:raw class="language-scss">
        p { font-size: 2rem; }

        @media (min-width: 768px) {
          p { font-size: 3rem; }
        }

        @media (min-width: 1200px) {
          p { font-size: 4rem; }
        }</code>
      </pre>
    </div>
  </div>

  <PNotes>
    <p>Before, fluid typography was often faked with a few breakpoint steps.</p>
    <p>
      At 767px the title is 2rem. At 768px it suddenly jumps to 3rem. There is
      no real in-between.
    </p>
    <p>The code says responsive, but the behavior is still stepped.</p>
    <p>
      Then move to clamp(): one declaration, continuous from floor to ceiling.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">clamp() — fluid type, no breakpoints</span> 🌊
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="clamp.css">
    <code is:raw class="language-scss">
    /* clamp(MIN, PREFERRED, MAX) */
    p {
        font-size: clamp(2rem, calc(5vw + 1rem), 4rem);
    }

    /* one declaration replaces a stack of media queries */
    section {
        padding-block: clamp(1rem, 4vw, 3rem);
    }</code>
  </pre>

  <PNotes>
    <p>Read the three args out loud: floor, ideal, ceiling.</p>
    <p>
      The middle value is the fluid one: it reacts to the viewport, but it can
      never go below the minimum or above the maximum.
    </p>
    <p>
      Avoid pure vw for text. Mixing vw with rem keeps the type fluid but still
      connected to the user's font settings.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<BrowserSupport
  feature="clamp()"
  chrome="79"
  firefox="75"
  safari="13.1"
  status="Baseline — widely available"
/>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">A fluid scale from one ratio</span> 🎚️
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="scale.css">
    <code is:raw class="language-scss">
    :root {
        --ratio: 1.25;
        --step-0: clamp(1rem, calc(0.9rem + 0.5vw), 1.25rem);
        --step-1: calc(var(--step-0) * var(--ratio));
        --step-2: calc(var(--step-1) * var(--ratio));
        --step-3: calc(var(--step-2) * var(--ratio));
    }

    h3 { font-size: var(--step-1); }
    h2 { font-size: var(--step-2); }
    h1 { font-size: var(--step-3); }</code>
  </pre>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      The base step is fluid, and the whole modular scale derives from one
      ratio.
    </p>
    <p>Change --ratio or --step-0 and the whole system reflows — at runtime.</p>
    <p>
      Same idea as color tokens: derived values, but computed directly by CSS.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Logical properties — writing-mode aware</span> 🌍
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="logical.css">
    <code is:raw class="language-scss">
    /* physical — assumes left-to-right, horizontal text */
    article { margin-left: 1rem; padding-top: 2rem; }

    /* logical — follows the writing direction */
    article {
        margin-inline-start: 1rem;
        padding-block-start: 2rem;
    }</code>
  </pre>

  <PNotes>
    <p>inline = text direction, block = perpendicular to it.</p>
    <p>
      It's not automatic internationalization, but it removes a huge
      left-to-right assumption from the design system.
    </p>
    <p>
      Better support for RTL and vertical writing modes starts by not
      hard-coding left, right, top and bottom everywhere.
    </p>
    <p>Transition into section 6 — context-aware components.</p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<BrowserSupport
  feature="Logical properties"
  chrome="89"
  firefox="66"
  safari="15"
  status="Baseline — widely available"
/>
